template.name: compactEnemy
template.parameter: const EnemyID_t id, const int speed, int health, const int damage, const int spawningTime, const bool kind

location.name: OnTrip
location.label: speed:10

OnTrip:
An enemy stays in this state (in the sense that only takes self-transitions) as long as MT is not reached and health>0: -> the "speed" delay is modeled as a exponential propability distribution of rate "speed/10"; -> if a message is received on "SHOOT_TO_ENEMY" (provided that it is alive) it executes "takeDamage" to process the possibly received shoot ("takeDamage" is also responsible of calling "dismiss").

location.name: BeforeSpawn
location.label: x<=spawningTime

BeforeSpawn:
An enemy starts its execution from this state, where it stays for an amount of time exactly equal to "spawningTime" before leaving.
Since in this state the "shoot_table[id].targettable" is set to false, it can't be targetted by turrets.
Once the spawningTime has expired, there are three possible transition through "OnTrip" and what changes between them is simply the value assigned to the variable "chosenPath": -> 0: the choice in junction (7,4) is "up" and the choice in junction (10,7) is "down"; -> 1: the choice in junction (7,4) is "up" and the choice in junction (10,7) is "right"; -> 2: the choice in junction (7,4) is "down".
In other words, the path to the MT an enemy will non-deterministically take is calculated right after the spawn and not upon arriving at a junction.

location.name: AfterShoot
location.label: speed:10

AfterShoot:
Once the enemy shot, it stays in this state until the delay expires (still modeled as an exponential propability distribution of rate "speed/10") and then it will leave the map (if not killed beforehands).

location.name: Dismissed
location.label:
Dismissed:
It is only a well-state where the enemy arrives when it "leaves the map". The absence of self-loops (stochastic models must not raise states where a delay is determined neiter by an invariant nor by a rate of exponential) will lead the system in deadlock once the match is ended. The presence of this kind of deadlocks however does not have an impact on interesting model behaviors since it is present only when the match is ended.

template.name: turret
template.parameter: const int id, const TurretConfiguration config

location.name: ReadyToShoot
location.label:
ReadyToShoot:
The turret stays in this state as long as there are no enemies to shoot. Otherwise, the most preffered of them is shot with "target".

location.name: Wait
location.label: 1:speed

Wait:
The turret stays in this state as long as the speed delay has not expired (delay is modeled as exponential probability distribution with rate "1/speed"). Once it is, it goes to ReadyToShoot and looks for enemies to shoot.

We set a considerably large amount of simulations: 1000. By default Uppaal used to verify it with 72 runs.
